The paper discusses a new approach to training generative models using unrolling a variational auto-encoder into a Markov chain and shaping the chain's trajectories using a technique inspired by recent work in Approximate Bayesian computation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper presents empirical results on the MNIST and TFD datasets, which are commonly used in computer vision research, indicating that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the use of regularization techniques used in reinforcement learning, suggesting that it may belong to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) or Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper's focus on shaping trajectories using a technique inspired by Approximate Bayesian computation suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY).
